WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.320
Hi, my name is Barret Schloerke, and I'm a software engineer at Posit, and I work on

00:00:11.320 --> 00:00:12.800
the Shiny team.

00:00:12.800 --> 00:00:18.780
And today, we're going to talk about ShinyLive, and what it can do for you by making serverless

00:00:18.780 --> 00:00:20.520
Shiny applications.

00:00:20.520 --> 00:00:24.000
Sounds odd, but it's pretty exciting when it's in practice.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:27.440
So what is ShinyLive?

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:34.279
When we do our typical Shiny deployment, we have one centralized server, or many centralized

00:00:34.279 --> 00:00:39.520
servers, but we have a server that is detached from the user's computers.

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:47.759
And this is where all your beef of your server computations are done, and it makes it so

00:00:47.759 --> 00:00:51.680
that you can have your secrets for your databases and everything like that.

00:00:51.680 --> 00:00:57.279
And then the user just gets this very thin UI within their browser.

00:00:57.279 --> 00:01:03.480
But ShinyLive kind of flips that up on its head and says, hey, I actually want to take

00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:09.440
this computation, and I want to distribute it to all of the users so that I don't have

00:01:09.440 --> 00:01:10.959
a centralized server.

00:01:10.959 --> 00:01:16.959
But instead, I send R, and I send the computations to the server's browser.

00:01:16.959 --> 00:01:22.360
And then it runs within their own machine on their own compute cycles, and they can

00:01:22.360 --> 00:01:26.959
look at all of the code within the app there.

00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:32.519
First off, saying this makes it seem like it's pretty trivial to do, but there's been

00:01:32.519 --> 00:01:37.760
years of work been done to try to make this possible to even allow R to run in the

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:43.080
browser. If I would have told myself 10 years ago that R could run in the browser, I

00:01:43.080 --> 00:01:47.440
would have laughed at you, and I still laugh because it's a crazy idea that just happens

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:48.519
to work today.

00:01:48.519 --> 00:01:54.239
And now, since R is within each user's browser, we don't need that centralized server.

00:01:54.239 --> 00:02:00.040
It is now distributed and infinitely horizontally scalable as long as you can send out

00:02:00.040 --> 00:02:01.199
the static resources.

00:02:01.519 --> 00:02:02.519
So let's check this out.

00:02:03.040 --> 00:02:07.199
Let's look at our old faithful from Shiny that has been updated.

00:02:07.559 --> 00:02:12.960
Let me refresh this here, even though I'm supposed to say, hey, demo, don't do anything

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:19.639
live. But this is actually going to refresh, download R, download all the things and get

00:02:19.639 --> 00:02:20.639
everything ready to go.

00:02:21.479 --> 00:02:23.119
And we have our old faithful app.

00:02:23.759 --> 00:02:27.360
We have a title in this, Hello Shiny, and the number of bins is 30.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.119
And then we have our plot that is done by base R graphics.

00:02:32.639 --> 00:02:34.119
So it's not something that you can fake.

00:02:35.839 --> 00:02:38.759
We'll change the bins and it quickly updates the plot.

00:02:40.759 --> 00:02:44.240
And I know it's hard to say like, oh, look at my servers.

00:02:44.639 --> 00:02:47.119
You know, I'm not doing something underneath the hood.

00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:52.080
This is under my own personal website and I'm an open source engineer.

00:02:52.479 --> 00:02:54.759
Like, I don't want to pay for anything if I don't have to.

00:02:55.199 --> 00:03:01.199
So all you can do is take my word for it that this is running live without opening up the

00:03:01.199 --> 00:03:03.119
console. But it's too hard to see on demo.

00:03:03.479 --> 00:03:09.479
So how is this done? This is done by the export function within the Shiny live R package.

00:03:09.759 --> 00:03:14.399
All you need to do is provide it your Shiny app folder and we will look around to find

00:03:14.399 --> 00:03:20.559
your app.R or UI.R server R or any combination that you have.

00:03:20.839 --> 00:03:23.839
We will then export this to a WebR Shiny app folder.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:30.240
It's something that's not an app.R folder, but or a folder that contains your app.R, but

00:03:30.240 --> 00:03:35.320
instead it's something that is exported using WebR and is ready to be hosted.

00:03:35.600 --> 00:03:40.119
And this is the requirement is that the exported folder must be hosted due to some

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:46.000
security requirements done by the WebR interactions, which is underneath the hood of

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:47.559
running R within your browser.

00:03:47.639 --> 00:03:51.839
We're kind of right now in the situation of, well, if I can host a folder, I can host a

00:03:51.839 --> 00:03:56.199
Shiny application, but we wouldn't want to host it on our own personal machine because,

00:03:56.240 --> 00:03:58.000
you know, I want to put my machine to sleep.

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:01.880
You can't visit my personal machine's web address easily.

00:04:02.399 --> 00:04:03.759
We would like it to be somewhere.

00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:10.199
And so this is where I get really excited because GitHub and GitHub actions have done a

00:04:10.199 --> 00:04:14.919
wonderful part for the open source community where your code is publicly available.

00:04:15.240 --> 00:04:22.720
So GitHub, along with GitHub pages, hosts your static websites and WebR is our static

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:25.760
asset. So this is this works out really well.

00:04:27.040 --> 00:04:32.119
We can use a GitHub action also, which is free for public repos.

00:04:32.279 --> 00:04:34.279
So we haven't had to pay anything yet.

00:04:35.239 --> 00:04:41.480
And using GitHub actions, we can run some sort of commit our Shiny live export command

00:04:41.519 --> 00:04:42.600
on every commit.

00:04:43.079 --> 00:04:48.559
And then once we've exported it, we can then upload that bundle to our website.

00:04:49.959 --> 00:04:54.959
And to do so, just make sure that you open up the settings within your website of

00:04:55.799 --> 00:05:00.880
settings, pages, build and deployment underneath source and GitHub actions.

00:05:00.920 --> 00:05:05.079
This location may change tomorrow, but at least that's where it is as of this recording.

00:05:05.519 --> 00:05:10.079
And I know I kind of blazed through that, but I just want to kind of reiterate what we've

00:05:10.119 --> 00:05:16.239
done. So for every commit that you do to a GitHub repo, you can have GitHub actions run

00:05:16.239 --> 00:05:20.320
in the background to do some work on your repo.

00:05:21.320 --> 00:05:23.239
It'll take your repo, check it out.

00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:25.519
It will then run Shiny live export.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:31.399
It'll then save that to a folder, will then take that folder and then upload it for our

00:05:31.399 --> 00:05:32.920
website to GitHub pages.

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:37.119
And this is all done for free as long as your repo is public.

00:05:37.119 --> 00:05:40.160
So let's look at what that action file will look like.

00:05:42.359 --> 00:05:48.399
So there we have this GitHub actions workflow.

00:05:48.839 --> 00:05:53.959
I would just call it, you know, deploy our app to GitHub pages and it runs on push to

00:05:53.959 --> 00:05:56.160
main or any other pull request.

00:05:56.959 --> 00:06:03.359
And then we have a job that we call Shiny live that uses a workflow that we have said

00:06:03.359 --> 00:06:08.799
Hey, I will take your app dot R and I will a folder or your repo that, you know, is a

00:06:08.799 --> 00:06:12.160
shiny app. And then I will turn it into your GitHub website.

00:06:12.399 --> 00:06:17.720
This way is, you know, as we're rapidly making developments within Shiny live, that

00:06:17.720 --> 00:06:20.040
contract will try to be maintained.

00:06:20.600 --> 00:06:24.839
And then that makes it so that you don't have to update all of your shiny apps moving

00:06:24.839 --> 00:06:28.440
forward. We just have one location that we need to install.

00:06:28.720 --> 00:06:30.799
There are some permissions that you can use.

00:06:30.959 --> 00:06:32.079
That we need to install.

00:06:32.440 --> 00:06:38.119
There are some permissions that you need to enable that we've added comments to, which is

00:06:38.119 --> 00:06:39.679
pages right and ID token right.

00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:47.640
This is required to publish the results to your website so that the proper permissions are

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:49.040
there, which are off by default.

00:06:49.720 --> 00:06:56.239
To simplify all of this, there is a single command that you can run within your repo so

00:06:56.239 --> 00:06:58.040
that you can get that GitHub action.

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:06.239
You can use the use this package and execute, use this GitHub action with the URL here, you

00:07:06.239 --> 00:07:11.440
can get this on the R Shiny live GitHub repo page and links will be below.

00:07:11.720 --> 00:07:14.959
So everything is all better.

00:07:14.959 --> 00:07:15.959
Everything's free now.

00:07:15.959 --> 00:07:16.920
We don't need to pay for anything.

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:20.320
Right. Like that's that's what happens now.

00:07:20.320 --> 00:07:30.920
Moving forward. Unfortunately, Gandalf wants you to keep it secret and he wants you to

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:40.040
keep it safe. But sadly, Gandalf is going to be really sad because the one problem with

00:07:40.040 --> 00:07:43.760
this whole approach with Shiny live is that there are no secrets.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:45.600
Everything is within the browser.

00:07:45.880 --> 00:07:52.679
So if you have a very savvy user, they will be able to find any secret environment

00:07:52.679 --> 00:07:57.200
variable, whatever you are using to run your Shiny application.

00:07:57.799 --> 00:08:04.600
It is available. But that is also an interesting part in that if you don't have any secrets,

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:12.119
you just have, you know, let's say a CSV, some logic in your app that are and you don't

00:08:12.119 --> 00:08:17.399
mind if someone inspects every single piece of it, then this is the perfect solution

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:20.239
because there are no secrets.

00:08:20.239 --> 00:08:24.640
And so it's OK. But if you do have a database that you want to keep secret, you can either

00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:32.000
hide it behind a plumber API or fast API somewhere else and then Shiny can call out to

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:38.239
it. You know, the location of that API will be public within your app, but the API's logic

00:08:38.239 --> 00:08:40.359
is then hidden away somewhere else.

00:08:40.799 --> 00:08:45.320
But your personal Shiny app can be then done with Shiny live.

00:08:46.440 --> 00:08:50.280
There have been questions as well about, well, what if I run it behind my firewall?

00:08:51.320 --> 00:08:57.840
Sure, no problem. It will be public to your company, you know, within the firewall.

00:08:58.200 --> 00:09:02.400
But obviously, since the firewall is there, I won't be able to access it.

00:09:02.719 --> 00:09:05.880
So you would only have to worry about bad actors within the company.

00:09:06.200 --> 00:09:07.520
And typically that's OK.

00:09:08.520 --> 00:09:13.400
But yes, the important part is the whole app is in the browser and users can inspect

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:16.320
everything somehow in the future.

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:22.440
We want to minimize the required usage of WebR so that you don't even know that you're

00:09:22.760 --> 00:09:24.640
using WebR along with Shiny live.

00:09:25.479 --> 00:09:27.840
And then we also want to minimize the start time.

00:09:28.359 --> 00:09:31.479
Today, when I was demoing it, it was about five seconds.

00:09:32.119 --> 00:09:35.440
And that's with cached R, cached packages and things like that.

00:09:36.119 --> 00:09:38.400
It used to be 30, 30 plus.

00:09:38.640 --> 00:09:43.880
And, you know, we hope to get it under the one second mark or as fast as we can by

00:09:43.880 --> 00:09:45.880
pre-bundling those applications.

00:09:45.919 --> 00:09:51.280
And so we're only doing the minimal amount of work at runtime and we can preload some

00:09:51.280 --> 00:09:52.400
of that heavy lifting.

00:09:52.679 --> 00:09:57.159
This would hopefully utilize some of our MetaCran repositories or even where you're

00:09:57.159 --> 00:09:59.039
within company Cran repositories.

00:09:59.479 --> 00:10:05.440
So if you have pre-built your different packages which are not on Cran or you have

00:10:05.679 --> 00:10:10.359
specific versions of things that you want to use, we can use our MetaCran instances and

00:10:10.359 --> 00:10:14.479
hopefully this will be a little more automatic.

00:10:15.119 --> 00:10:20.000
And so you don't need to manually say point here, point here for all of my 50 packages.

00:10:20.280 --> 00:10:27.119
And then this is leading up to making custom bundles using GitHub actions so that you

00:10:27.159 --> 00:10:32.159
yourself don't need to have a developer environment for exporting ShinyLive or web R

00:10:32.239 --> 00:10:35.039
applications, sorry, R libraries.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:41.400
Instead, we'll have a GitHub action and we just send a small command, you wait a little

00:10:41.400 --> 00:10:47.119
bit and then let GitHub do all the heavy lifting and then it'll send you back a tar

00:10:47.119 --> 00:10:50.159
ball or zip folder of special information.

00:10:50.479 --> 00:10:54.799
But all that leads up to the fastest start time that we can possibly get.

00:10:55.239 --> 00:10:59.080
So to recap, we have positive R ShinyLive.

00:10:59.320 --> 00:11:03.840
The main function within that ShinyLive package is the export function where you're

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:08.880
going to export it from the folder from here to there and then we'll take that folder to

00:11:08.880 --> 00:11:17.000
there and host it using GitHub actions or GitHub pages and everything throughout that

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:22.400
whole pipeline is free to users today given that you're using a public repo.

00:11:23.400 --> 00:11:28.880
Just remember, there are no secrets and so don't put your database in there, database

00:11:28.880 --> 00:11:33.400
connection information that you want to keep secret that would normally be held secret

00:11:33.440 --> 00:11:36.719
when doing a traditional Shiny server deployment.

